title: For Sale:  Bushmaster AR-15 A2 Style Camp Perry Limited Edition 20" Heavy Barrel
postcontent:
This is a Bushmaster before Freedom Group got a hold of them.  Quality gun out of Windham, ME.  Gun comes with 100 rounds of match Hornady ammunition.  Comes with 2 original 20 round bushmaster magazines, and a special five round magazine for DCM match shooting.  Gun has original case and cardboard box that it came in.  I am firm on $1700.  Not only is this the perfect match rifle, but you can put any upper on it you want.  Butt stock can easily be changed to magpul and you can have a lightweight carbine and a match rifle with 5 minutes of your time.  I have a scope mount and scope for the A2 style if you are interested let me know as it is not included in the $1700.  Below is a description of all the features this rifle has:

Camp Perry Limited Edition #43 of 100. Camp Perry insignia etched on receiver. This rife is specifically designed for DCM match competitions.  In keeping with DCM competition rules, this rifle looks like a stock AR15 (although it is far from stock). The A2 Rear Sight is specially modified to accept interchangeable micro-aperture peeps and its windage and elevation mechanisms feature either 1/2 or 1/4 MOA adjustments with each click of the windage knob or elevation dial.  The competition front sight is specially ground for optimum clarity. It is secured within the front sight base by a set screw to avoid the possibility of any movement. The 20" Bushmaster extra heavy competition barrel is a full 1" diameter under the handguard. They are machined from chrome moly vanadium barrel steel and are hardened to Rockwell C26 to 32 - which are superior to stainless barrels.  In the upper receiver, the bolt is carefully matched to the barrel extension for maximum strength and accuracy. The lower receiver houses a finely honed competition trigger job that is factory set for a DCM legal 3.5 lb. 1st Stage and a 1 lb. letoff (2nd Stage). The handguard set looks like stock gov't issue parts but is actually a free float type handguard (handguard/barrel nut combination) that does not contact the barrel. Special weights are installed inside this free floater handguard for added stability. Even the buttstock has been improved for competition with the addition of a lead counterbalancing weight.

title: For Sale:  ( ͡° ͜ʖ ͡°)S&W .38/44 Heavy Duty (sold pending funds)
postcontent:
(sold pending funds)
Collectible Smith & Wesson Revolver .38/44 Heavy Duty Model of 1950.

(I will include a buch of +p ammo I have also)

It is a postwar - Pre Model 20. (manufactured 1958 or 59) production ceased 1960. It is a .38 S&W Special, (or .38/44 which was like a really hot ++P load)  4" barrel, Short throw hammer, It is a high gloss blue that is original and at around 98%, The original grips at 92%. I can find no wear on the frame but there is the usual drag mark on the cylinder of a used gun. The bore remains as new. Locks up tight and right. This model was offered by S&W from 1946 to 1950 and I am told about 2500 were made with the 4" Barrel, though some gunsmiths were known to convert them to .357 mags, they are that tough. This gun is a full recessed and pinned revolver. Highly desirable and can shoot the hottest of .38 loads available. Do some research if you haven't heard of this gun. An older Blue Book of Gun Values puts this gun at $1000 for 95%. Even though I rate this gun at an easy 95% and more likely 96%, a real world attitude and the economy makes me put it at $750.00 All matching serial numbers on Frame, barrel, yoke, and stocks. Serious interested buyers can shoot me a message for more detailed pictures if desired.

NO TRADES 

HISTORY OF THE 38-44 HEAVY DUTY

In late 1929 and early 1930, due to armored vests and bulletproof glass for autos, the various big gangs around the country gave our police and law enforcement agencies a bad time. Colt answered the problem with the Super.38 Auto on the good old model 1911 design. The new arm shot a 130 grain bullet at 1300 feet and proved an answer to the problem. J . Edgar Hoover's boys promptly adopted it for their side-arm. It would penetrate bulletproof vests, armored car bodies if not too heavy, and bulletproof glass. The .38 S& W Special had been loaded with smokeless powder to equal the same velocity as it had achieved with black powder. As MAJ Doug Wesson analyzed the problem, he soon came to the realization that the answer was to increase the powder in the .38 Special. The answer was the .38/.44 S&W Special or the .38 High Velocity. Smith & Wesson soon realized during testing that this round was too hot for their standard Military and Police .38 Specials. A new model gun was needed to handle the increased pressure and recoil brought by the new round. In December of 1929, the order to build 500 .38/.44 Militaries as they were originally called was issued by Harold Wesson. The first orders were placed in early December 1929 which would indicate that the factory had announced the intent to manufacture them in late 1929. The new .38/.44 Heavy Duty was identical in construction to S&W 's earlier .44 Hand Ejector Third Model, with the exception of its .38 chambering. Initially the gun was only offered with a 5" barrel, with a choice of blue or nickel finishes, weighing in at 40 ounces and checkered walnut service stocks. In November 1931, Smith & Wesson began production of the .38/.44 Outdoorsman which was an adjustable sighted Heavy Duty. On January 14, 1935 Harold Wesson ordered the factory to forge and machine 100 each 4" .38/.44 barrels. There are recorded instances where 6.5 inch barreled Heavy Duties were manufactured. There are also instances where the Heavy Duty was manufactured in .45 Colt caliber. The 38/44 Heavy Duty was the most popular N framed gun in the 1930s with 11,111 manufactured before WWII halted production. The high speed .38 round in the .38/.44 led Doug Wesson, Winchester, and Phil Sharp to collaborate on a new, more powerful .38 caliber round they called the .357 S& W Magnum. The new gun they built it around was a Hand Ejector with adjustable sights called the Registered Magnum. After WWII, S& W began shipping 38/44 Heavy Dutys in the summer of 1946. These guns were Transition models which had pre war and post war characteristics. These models continued until 1950 when the 38/44 Heavy Duty Model of 1950 was produced. There were over 8,700 transition Heavy Dutys manufactured between 1946-1950. The post war catalogs listed the Heavy Duty as available in 4, 5 and 6.5 inch barrel lengths, blue or nickel. Production of the Heavy Duty continued until the early 1960s when they were called the Model 20. The known Model 20s were shipped in 1963. The last known Model marked guns, Model 20- 2s were shipped in late 1964 to Austin Police Department. In 1966, the Model 20 was dropped from the catalog.


References: The History of Smith & Wesson, 1852-1945, Robert J . Neal and Roy G. Jinks. Sixguns , Elmer Keith

title: For Sale:  ( ͡° ͜ʖ ͡°)8mm Italian Carcano W/ ammo
postcontent:
Italian 7.92 Carcano (8MM Mauser) Enblock Carbine Rifle 1938 $250.00 O.N.O.

(Have ammo too)

The wood has the usual ding, dents and scratches, but they are all war time attrition, not recent. there are no cracks in the stock. No major surface rust or pitting visible on the gun, except a little dirty in the nooks and crannies under my light magnifier. The bore is shiny and bright with decent looking rifling. The visible serial number 0014 is the same on the receiver as on the barrel. The number on the stock is 60274. I do not see any numbers on the bolt or elswhere. The firing pin is present and looks good. There is no enlargement of the firing pin hole in the bolt face and it hold the round nice with no slop and extracts and ejects correctly. I have not disassembled the gun to further check it out either. The barrel crown looks good and there is no visible throat erosion. The throat edges are are clean and square not beveled or dinged. There is also an aluminum tag on the trigger guard that has the number ss45182 on it. Probably from some previous auction. This gun was probably worked up post WWII by the Italians for the Egyptians or the Israelis. (wasn't that nice of them to sell to both sides of a conflict?) Since there is no star on the rifle, the consensus seems to be Egyptian. I like how low the serial number is. There are no import marks or engravings of an american distributor on the gun. Great piece of history and fun to shoot. Comes with a box of 8mm surplus Yugo ammo and one enblock style clip. (new production clip, readily available and inexpensive)

Sorry, I don't have the original box and papers. Gun is in good fireable shape. It has been in the safe for many years only to be pulled and cleaned and inspected. Look at my other ads also. I will be selling the bulk of my collection over the next month or so to fund a large project. I will have some things for sale that will interest all different collectors and shooters.

Sales Order:

If the ad is up and I do not list it as "sale pending" then it is still for sale. Do not message me with "do you still have it" or "is it still available". I will assume you are a spam bot trying to get my email address and I will ignore you. "I am interested" is a close second that is being used also. I myself answer an ad with where I am located and when I would be available. That always gets a persons attention

Sales Order:

If the ad is up and I do not list it as "sale pending" then it is still for sale. Do not message me with "do you still have it" or "is it still available". I will assume you are a spam bot trying to get my email address and I will ignore you. "I am interested" is a close second that is being used also. I myself answer an ad with where I am located and when I would be available. That always gets a persons attention. I try to sell to the first person who contacts me first. After that I contact the second response and so on. This had always worked for me in the past, but as time changed and more people flaked on me or wanted me to wait beyond an agreed upon time/day, I have changed my method to a "first with the cash gets the prize". As in everything communication is king, I can't read your mind. I am not interested in Shipping a gun anywhere. If I was, I would be advertising it to a national audience auction site and asking more. Like all things, If I get enough ridiculous offers and somebody just has to have this because it reminds them of the one dear old dad used to have and has more dollars than the local's sense, I will ship to your local FFL if he will accept a direct ship gun from a private owner. Disclaimers and Information:

I am not a gun shop, there is no sales tax or background fees. I do not take credit cards. I also will not accept a cashier's check, personal check, money order or anything other than CASH. If you email me a low-ball offer and say that you will pay in CASH, like it is something special and I am selling a used car, I will assume you are a effing retard who shouldn't own a gun to begin with. Contact me and I will email the best pictures I can manage. No, I am not a professional photographer. I do not look at my phone all day hoping I have email. I check it when I get home from work and occasionally on the week ends. Please don't get discouraged and think I am ignoring you if I don't return an email in 5 minutes. I am not willing to drive across the state to meet you so that you can inspect the gun and make me an offer. Driving halfway across town is a different matter all together, but I hope you will have made your offer ahead of time. If not, I may take my toys and go home. Yes, I know what the asking price on Gunbroker is, I also know what they sell for along with shipping and transfer fee and credit card fee. I do not dignify ridiculous offers with a reasonable response, they will get a ridiculous response, if any response at all. I do not NEED to sell anything, I would just LIKE to. Reasonable offers are considered, not necessarily accepted, but considered. Please do not drag the moral character of my relatives into any disagreement, I can't help it, they are like that. Mom in particular. All firearms should be considered loaded at all times, they may not be, but it is safer to consider them that way. Spammers and scammers beware, I have a loaded LOIC (low orbit ion cannon) and I know how to use it.

P.S.

title: For Sale:  DETAILS OF "ASSAULT WEAPONS" BAN
location: NO MORE GUN CONTROL, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
According to a January 25th release by the NRA the newly introduced Feinstein ban would:

"

Ban the sale, transfer, manufacture or importation of 157 named firearms. Presumably, these were chosen by looking at pictures, as Sen. Feinstein has said she did before introducing her first legislation on the issue in 1993.

Ban all semi-automatic rifles that can accept a detachable magazine.  This is because the bill would ban any semi-automatic detachable-magazine rifle that has even one "feature," particularly a pistol grip—which is defined to include any "characteristic that can function as a grip." Other features that would cause a rifle to be banned include a forward grip; folding, telescoping, or detachable stock; grenade launcher or (as an absurd propaganda move) rocket launcher; barrel shroud; or a threaded barrel. 

Ban all detachable-magazine semi-auto pistols that have any of the following: a threaded barrel, second pistol grip, or magazine that mounts anywhere other than the grip. The bill would also ban any handgun that is a semi-automatic version of a fully automatic handgun.

Ban all semi-automatic rifles and handguns that have fixed magazines that accept more then 10 rounds.

Ban all semi-automatic shotguns that have just one of the following: a folding, telescoping, or detachable stock; a pistol grip; a fixed magazine that can accept more than five rounds, a detachable magazine; a forward grip; a revolving cylinder; or a grenade or rocket launcher. As with the rifle provision, this could potentially ban any semi-auto shotgun, because all of them have "characteristics that can function as a grip." And of course, countless Americans have pistol-grip shotguns for home defense.

Ban all belt-fed semi-automatic firearms, such as semi-auto replicas of historic machine guns.

Ban all frames or receivers of banned guns, even though in many cases they are identical to the frames and receivers of guns that would not be banned.

Ban "combinations of parts" from which "assault weapons" can be assembled. Read broadly, this could ban the acquisition of a single spare part that could be combined with parts you already own.

Ban any "part, combination of parts, component, device, attachment, or accessory that is designed or functions to accelerate the rate of fire of a semiautomatic rifle"--a vague definition that could ban items such as competition trigger parts.

Ban the sale or transfer of all ammunition feeding devices that hold more than ten rounds. Even those lawfully possessed before passage of the bill could never be transferred, even to your heirs through a will.

"

Yes, your semi-auto tubular magazine .22 is now an "assault weapon", arguably, so is your Remington 1187 duck gun since the stock is "detachable". Got a defensive semi-auto shotgun like a Mossberg 930 SPX, Remington 1100, OR 1187 etc that has a tubular magazine that takes more than 5 rounds? Yep, that's a banned "assault weapon" too.
